occurrences.line_text: Into their caues, their heads from death to hide,
Ne any left, that victorie to him enuide.
Then backe returning to his dearest deare,
He her gan to recomfort, all he might,
And forth her bringing to the ioyous light,
Deuiz'd all goodly meanes, from her to driue
He did them all to Coridon restore.
To shew the courtesie by him profest,
To his atchieuement of the Blatant beast;
Whilst none was him to stop, nor none him to restraine.
Whilst none was him to stop, nor none him to restraine.
This daughter thought in wedlocke to haue bound
Of loue to Bellamoure empierced were,
By all meanes shund to match with any forrein fere.
And closely did her wed, but knowne to few.
That neither could to company of th'other creepe.
That to his loue sometimes he came in place,
Whereof her wombe vnwist to wight was fraught,
Should know thereof, to slay he would haue sought,
Deliuered to her handmayd, that for hyre
The litle babe, to take thereof a sight.
To weet what mortall hand, or heauens grace
Came to the place, where when he wrapped found
Were turnd, and they to freedome did retyre.
Vntill the damzell gan to wex more sound and strong.
Tho gan Sir Calidore him to aduize
Asham'd to thinke, how he that enterprize,
Bequeath'd to him, forslacked had so sore;
Therefore resoluing to returne in hast
To leaue his Loue, now perill being past,
Throughout the world, and to destruction brought.
Whom to recomfort, all the meanes he wrought,
With thanks to Bellamour and Claribell,
In this exploite, me needeth to declare,
What did betide to the faire Pastorell,
To cherish her with all things choice and rare;
Appointed to attend her dewly day and night.
Chaunst to espy vpon her yuory chest
Which well auizing, streight she gan to cast
To Fortunes spoile, vnable it to ayd.
To Fortunes spoile, vnable it to ayd.
To tell her, how the heauens had her graste,
To saue her chylde, which in misfortunes mouth was plaste.
Whilest ye in durance dwelt, ye to me gaue
The same againe if now ye list to haue,
And gan to question streight how she it knew.
Whereof her name ye then to her did giue.
The matrone stayd no lenger to enquire,
But forth in hast ran to the straunger Mayd;
That this young Mayd, whom chance to her presents
That monstrous Beast by finall force to quell,
And to the Clergy now was come at last;
That endlesse were to tell. The Elfin Knight,
Were yrkesome to report; yet that foule Beast
And ransacke all their dennes from most to least,
Did cast to ground, whilest none was them to rew;
Did cast to ground, whilest none was them to rew;
With open mouth, that seemed to containe
And some of Tygres, that did seeme to gren,
And bet abacke, threatning in vaine to bite,
But he right well aware, his rage to ward,
That backeward he enforced him to fall:
Of butchers balefull hand to ground is feld,
To be downe held, and maystred so with might,
Striuing in vaine to rere him selfe vpright.
To crop his thousand heads, the which still new
And sharpely at him to reuile and raile,
At last when as he found his force to shrincke,
And rage to quaile, he tooke a muzzell strong
To see the hatefull sunne, that he might tell
To griesly Pluto, what on earth was donne,
And to the other damned ghosts, which dwell
Him liberty was left aloud to rore:
To see him leade that Beast in bondage strong,
Reioyced much to see his captiue plight,
And many causelesse caused to be blamed:
To mortall men, then he had done before;
Ne spareth he most learned wits to rate,
Hope to escape his venemous despite,
That neuer so deserued to endite.
And seeke to please, that now is counted wisemens threasure.
But Terpine borne to'a more vnhappy howre,
With loathly frogs and toades, which eyes did lacke,
Like loathly Toades, some fashioned in the wast
But toades and frogs, his pasture poysonous,
There, whether it diuine Tobacco were,
The God, though loth, yet was constraind t'obay,
The huge seas vnder her t'obay her seruaunts law.
To reskew his owne Lord, but thought it iust t'obay.
There bound t'obay that Amazons proud law,
T'obay the heasts of mans well ruling hand,
T'obay a womans tyrannous direction,
T'obey their riders hest, as seemed good.
T'obserue the sacred lawes of armes, that are assynd.
More then his loue, which thus ye seeke t'obtaine.
Betweene his cankred teeth a venemous tode,
From top to toe no place appeared bare,
Next him was Feare, all arm'd from top to toe,
Ne feeles the thorns and thickets pricke her tender toes.
As one in feare the Stygian gods t'offend,
Who[m] sure he weend, that he some wher tofore had eide.
And then too well beleeu'd, that which tofore
For that beastes teeth, which wounded you tofore,
Them both together laid, to ioy in vaine delight.
Long time they thus together traueiled,
With hideous horrour both together smight,
All these together in one heape were throwne,
The which my life and loue together tyde?
Together with his Squire, arayed meet:
And eke as pledges firme, right hands together ioynd.
As on the way together we did fare,
With thornes together pind and patched was,
Heaped together in rude rablement
So both together fiers engrasped bee,
So goodly purpose they together fond,
So to the riuers side they both together far'd.
They courteous conge tooke, and forth together yode.
She graunted, and then in they all together far'd.
Together with the king of Louthiane,
And forth together went, with sorrow fraught.
Vnfitly yokt together in one teeme,
Together with impetuous rage and forse,
Thus long they three together traueiled,
It fortuned as they together far'd,
Were heap'd together with the vulgar sort,
All which together sung full chearefully
So seemd those two, as growne together quite,
So foorth they went, and both together giusted;
With which it blessed Concord hath together tide.
Do meete together, each abacke rebowndes
That on a time as they together way'd,
Doe meete together on the watry lea,
So well accorded forth they rode together
A trompet blew; they both together met,
With that they both together fiercely met,
And by the tailes together firmely bound,
Those warlike champions both together chose,
Together with this Hag beside her set,
So furiously they both together met,
That forcibly to ground they both together went.
As two wild Boares together grapling go,
So both together giue a new allarme,
So all together stird vp strifull stoure,
But on their common harmes together did deuise.
And chearelesse hunger, they together spent;
The Ladies both on horse, together fast embraced.
When all three kinds of loue together meet,
Whom straight the Prince ensuing, in together far'd.
But when a while they had together beene,
They liu'd together long without debate:
Thus many miles they two together wore,
They saw together skirmishing, as seemed:
Met here together; where through lewd vpbraide
That as we ride together on our way,
All these together by themselves did sport
That euer were on earth, all were they set together.
And both her feete and legs together twyned
Both linckt together neuer to dispart,
All these together marched toward Proteus hall.
And now together on their way they bin,
Together ran with ready speares in rest.
There being both together in the floud,
There they together stroue and struggled long,
Then would he ballaunce heauen and hell together,
And put two wrongs together to be tride,
And then together doe them both compare.
The trompets sound; then all together ronne.
Together met, of all to make an end.
They both together ioyned might and maine,
Streight way so soone as both together met,
Both brethren, whom one wombe together bore,
Together stroue, and kindled wrathfull fires:
Together with her selfe in dowry free;
Together with sir Terpin all that night:
But bath'd in bloud and sweat together ment;
The Trumpets sound, and they together run
So both together ylike felly bent,
Together met, and strongly either strooke
Thus goe they both together to their geare,
And their sharpe speares doe both together smite
Tho as they rode together on their way,
Flocking together in confusde array,
The trompets sound, and they together goe,
By the way side being together set,
And linckt together gainst Sir Artegall,
Together with this Ladie, passing on the plaine.
This day, as he and I together roade
Whilest they together for the quarrey stroue,
Ioying together in vnblam'd delight,
They met together in that luckelesse glade;
So as they past together on their way,
Of which whilest they discoursed both together,
Who her together with his Squyre
Lo where a knight together with his squire,
Therefore conspiring all together plaine,
And forth together rode a comely couplement.
So forth they rode together all in troupe,
So both together traueld, till they met
Gathered him selfe together soone againe,
Gathered together, and them homeward bare:
One day when as the shepheard swaynes together
In such discourses they together spent
One day as they all three together went
Doe fall together, stryuing each to get
So forth they goe together (God before)
Thenceforth they ioy'd in happinesse together,
There they a while together thus did dwell
After their wearie sweat and bloudy toile,
Who seekes with painfull toile, shall honour soonest find.
Refuse such fruitlesse toile, and present pleasures chuse.
Where through long watch, & late dayes weary toile,
When too huge toile and labour them constraines:
Into the hunters toile, doth rage and rore,
After late weary toile, which she had tride
Those weaker Ladies after weary toile;
Long were to tell the trauell and long toile,
Weary of toile and trauell of that day,
After that long daies toile and weary plight.
With wearie trauell and vncertaine toile,
This bottle thus before you with such toile,
His former quest, so full of toile and paine;
Through euery place, with restlesse paine and toile
For she is wearie of the toilesome way,
His sandales were with toilesome trauell torne,
Behold, Ã´ man, that toilesome paines doest take
Here take thy louers token on thy pate.
Imprinted had that token of his wrath,
Which speaking token sheweth at the least
And them coniur'd by some well knowen token,
Ne any token doth thereof abide:
And token true to old Eumenias,
It as a token of good fortune tooke.
And thus vpbrayding sayd; This token beare
That mote remaine for an eternall token
A priuy token, which betweene them past,
Yet shewd some token of his gentle blood,
The Prince according to the former token,
Which when he heard, and saw the tokens trew,
Yet further right by tokens to descrie,
He askt, what priuie tokens he did beare.
Was Artegall, by many tokens plaine;
As tokens of her thankefull mind beseene,
And by rude tokens made to her appeare
Ne yours conceiue, ne but by tokens speake:
He told of Saintes and Popes, and euermore
Eftsoones I thought her such, as she me told,
And so forth told the story of her feare:
Who told her all that fell in iourney as she went.
And on the top a Diall told the timely howres.
And in his lap an heape of coine he told;
Abide, till I haue told the message, which I haue.
Too late it was, to Satyres to be told,
But that false Pilgrim, which that leasing told,
This is my cause of griefe, more great, then may be told.
Of that same hornes great vertues weren told,
But all the floore (too filthy to be told)
Whose secret filth good manners biddeth not be told.
But told it flames, and hidden it does glow,
The wofull tale that Treuisan had told,
Made him forget all that Fidelia told.
Whose passing price vneath was to be told;
That their exceeding merth may not be told:
Resort, to heare of straunge aduentures to be told.
Of whose fowle deedes, too hideous to be told
And told the storie of the mortall payne,
And told for secret how he vnderstood
And told that gardins pleasures in their caroling.
And in his lap a masse of coyne he told,
He there beheld, too long here to be told:
Foreby that idle strond, of him were told,
Was neuer wight, that treason of him told;
Now to Pyrrochles many strokes he told;
Well weeting trew, what she had rashly told;
As in that old mans booke they were in order told.
It told, how first Prometheus did create
And told her meaning in her countenaunce;
Which spent in vaine, at last she told her briefe,
Through hope of those, which Merlin had her told
Which to his mother told, despeire she from her flong.
Of Amoret is told.
Nor doubt himselfe; and who he was, her told.
He rou'd at her, and told his secret care:
Deuized hath, and to her louer told.
Oppressed her, and there (as it is told)
Who backe returning, told as he had seene,
Amongst the which they told, as then befell,
Shall else be told in order, as it fell.
To whom they told all, that did them betide,
And told his Dame, her Squire of low degree
And told at large how that same errant Knight,
Yet hoping griefe may lessen being told,
Which when he had vnto his mother told,
So he her told: but soone as she did heare
Faith may be giuen, it is by them told,
Till they had told their message word by word:
That whylome hath of Hercules bene told,
She daily told, her loue he did defye,
And him she told, her Dame his freedome did denye.
She told but moneths, to make them seeme more few:
He to her told the story of that fray,
But when they of that yron man had told,
To weete if it were true, as she had told;
Of pompous show, much more then she had told;
But like a cloud, as likest may be told,
So to the Church he came, where it was told,
To Faery Court, where what him fell shall else be told.
And that knights berd for toll, which they for passage pay.
That dedicated is t'Olympicke Ioue,
To decke his herce, and trap his tomb-blacke steed.
And the hid treasures in her sacred tombe,
Therewith both Squire and dwarfe did tomble downe
That downe he tombled; as an aged tree,
He tombled on an heape, and wallowd in his gore.
Of his strong foe, lay tombled in the myre,
Transfixed with the speare, downe tombled ded
He tombling rudely downe to ground did rush,
His tombling billowes rolls with gentle rore:
Quite through his braine. He tombling downe on ground,
Like a great water flood, that tombling low
For tombling into mischiefe vnespide.
From the swift Barry, tombling downe apace,
He tombling downe, with gnashing teeth did bite
So sore, that tombling backe, he downe did slyde
His head before him tombling on the ground.
Strong Allo tombling from Slewlogher steep,
Which tombling downe vpon the senselesse ground,
O helpe thou my weake wit, and sharpen my dull tong.
And lickt her lilly hands with fawning tong,
And lilled forth his bloudie flaming tong:
With foltring tong, and trembling euery vaine,
Of mother pearle, and buckled with a golden tong.
Of perle and precious stone, that earthly tong
His practick wit, and his faire filed tong,
And catching hold of her vngratious tong,
And therein shut vp his blasphemous tong,
A paire of redwhot yron tongs did take
Till she had duld the sting, which in her tongs end grew.
To sharpen him, and their owne cursed tongs did straine.
And therein were a thousand tongs empight,
And well could file his tongue as smooth as glas;
His haire, and hastie tongue, that did offend:
Thy sad tongue cannot tell more heauy plight,
And euery head with fyrie tongue did flame,
And foltring tongue at last these words seemd forth to shake.
His subtill tongue, like dropping honny, mealt'th
With lips full pale and foltring tongue opprest,
My tongue can tell, so farre all sense they pas:
And euer as she went, her tongue did walke
Your curteous tongue, his prayses to compile,
Her lying tongue was in two parts diuided,
And as her tongue, so was her hart discided,
She arm'd her tongue, and thought at him to scold;
Nathlesse her tongue not to her will obayd,
The whiles his babling tongue did yet blaspheme
With many more, whose names no tongue can tell.
That from thy tongue thy hearts intent doth hold.
Her burning tongue with rage inflamed hath,
So smooth of tongue, and subtile in his tale.
Some one, whose tongue was for his trespasse vyle
That well could charme his tongue, and time his speach
In which her cursed tongue full sharpe and short
She with the sting, which in her vile tongue grew,
Whom with vile tongue and venemous intent
Your eies, your eares, your tongue, your talk restraine
A wicked Monster, that his tongue doth whet
Her pleasing tongue, that soone she pacifyde
Her tongue to her restord, then thus she sayd;
That twixt his pleasing tongue, and her faire hew,
With his vile tongue, which many had defamed,
All which not if an hundred tongues to tell,
So dreadfully his hundred tongues did bray,
The which did seeme a thousand tongues to haue,
But most of them were tongues of mortall men,
The tongues of Serpents with three forked stings,
By force, he gan his hundred tongues apply,
With which some wicked tongues did it backebite,
And one great chimney, whose long tonnell thence,
Me, all too meane, the sacred Muse areeds
And raise my thoughts too humble and too vile,
And raise my thoughts too humble and too vile,
But of his cheere did seeme too solemne sad;
But wander too and fro in wayes vnknowne,
Least suddaine mischiefe ye too rash prouoke:
I better wot then you, though now too late
The one of them he gaue a message too,
Yrkesome of life, and too long lingring night.
And eke themselues too rudely rigorous,
O too deare loue, loue bought with death too deare.
O too deare loue, loue bought with death too deare.
Her vp he tooke, too simple and too trew,
Her vp he tooke, too simple and too trew,
All night she thinks too long, and often lookes for light.
Saying, that harlot she too lately knew,
Himselfe too nigh at hand, but turned wyde
O then too weake and feeble was the forse
Least thou of her beleeue too lightly blame,
As enuying her selfe, that too exceeding shone.
And that great Princesse too exceeding prowd,
Alone he wandring thee too long doth want:
That whylome was to me too dearely deare.
His heart too high through his great riches store;
Proud Tarquin, and too lordly Lentulus,
Yet sad he was that his too hastie speed
Nor too much to prouoke; for he would learne
Too late it was, to Satyres to be told,
Then that thou hadst repented it too late?
And guide his wearie gate both too and fro:
But all the floore (too filthy to be told)
Whose presence I haue lackt too long a day;
For she was proud, and of too high intent,
That this her knight was feeble, and too faint;
Too high a ditty for my simple song;
His feeble sence, and too exceeding shyne.
The yielding aire, which nigh too feeble found
To trusse the pray too heauie for his flight;
Himselfe in streighter bandes too rash implyes,
Did come too neare, and with his talants play,
And often blame the too importune fate,
My ragged rimes are all too rude and bace,
Too false and strong for earthly skill or might,
But yield his sence to be too blunt and bace,
Death were too little paine for such a foule despight.
Speake, O deare Lady speake: help neuer comes too late.
Yt nought too deare I deemd, while so my dear I sought.
Accusing fortune, and too cruell fate,
One thought their cheare too litle, th'other thought too mutch.
One thought their cheare too litle, th'other thought too mutch.
But of her loue too lauish (litle haue she thancke.)
Of whose fowle deedes, too hideous to be told
Which mariage make; that day too farre did seeme:
(That day it selfe him seemed all too long:)
Or with the hidden fire too inly warmd.
He there beheld, too long here to be told:
As ouercome with too exceeding might,
Certes, Sir knight, ye bene too much to blame,
But that too oft she chaung'd her natiue hew:
That either me too bold ye weene, this wise
Whose wanton pleasures him too much did please.
The wretched man gan then auise too late,
Too truely tryde in his extreamest state;
That sacked Rome too dearely did assay,
He left two sonnes, too young to rule aright,
(O too high ditty for my simple rime.)
That were too long their infinite contents
His falsed faith, and loue too lightly flit,
Did decke her, and too lauishly adorne,
Too well we see, (said they) and proue too well
Too well we see, (said they) and proue too well
Did roll too highly, and too often glaunce,
Did roll too highly, and too often glaunce,
But fierce Bacchante seemd too fell and keene;
Her loue too light, to wooe a wandring guest:
That in their proper prayse too partiall bee,
But ah my rimes too rude and rugged arre,
Least that too farre ye haue your sorrow sought:
Both leafe and fruit, both too vntimely shed,
When too huge toile and labour them constraines:
Too rathe cut off by practise criminall
For all too long I burne with enuy sore,
Least afterwards it be too late to take thy flight.
Least his too haughtie hardines might reare
A lesson too too hard for liuing clay,
A lesson too too hard for liuing clay,
Too true the famous Marinell it fownd,
The guilt I doe ascribe: deare wisedome bought too late.
And chase away this too long lingring night,
But froward fortune, and too forward Night
And euery one her answerd, that too late
His feeble eyne, with too much brightnesse dazed,
Who when too late awaking, well they kent,
That challenge did too peremptory seeme,
And knightly worth, which he too late did try,
Which th'old man seeing well, who too long thought
But all in vaine, his woman was too wise,
And he too simple euer to surprise
Sith late he fled from his too earnest foe:
One may his iourney bring too soone to euill end.
Nor seeme too suddeinly him to inuade:
Be not too bold; whereto though she did bend
Whose too long absence him had sore annoyd,
For which no seruice she too much esteemed,
That were too long a worke to count them all;
This knight too late his manhood and his might,
But Paridell that had too late a tryall
Too boastfull Blandamour, too long I beare
Too boastfull Blandamour, too long I beare
Too foolish Paridell, that fayrest floure
But too and fro in great amazement reel'd,
Out of the swowne, in which too long he lay;
He all that night, that too long night did passe.
My Sire, who me too dearely well did loue,
Which for it is too long here to abide,
Enuying my too great felicity,
These gentle Ladies will misdeeme too light,
And eke too loose of life, and eke of loue too light.
And eke too loose of life, and eke of loue too light.
She bad to lighten my too heauie band,
And being brought in daunger, to relent too late.
That I too true by triall haue approued:
Through his too ventrous prowesse proued ouer all.
